# 📌 967. Numbers With Same Consecutive Differences

## 🧠 Problem Summary
Given two integers `n` and `k`, return all non-negative integers of length `n` such that the absolute difference between every two consecutive digits is `k`.

---

## 🚀 Approach (Backtracking / DFS)

- Build numbers **digit by digit**
- Start from digits `1 → 9` (no leading zero)
- At each step:
  - Next digit = `lastDigit + k`
  - Next digit = `lastDigit - k`
- Continue until length becomes `n`

---

## ⚠️ Important Points
- If `k == 0`, avoid duplicate paths
- Digits must be between `0 → 9`
- Special case: if `n == 1`, return `0 → 9`

---

## ✅ Java Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int[] numsSameConsecDiff(int n, int k) {
        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();

        if (n == 1) {
            for (int i = 0; i <= 9; i++) result.add(i);
        } else {
            for (int i = 1; i <= 9; i++) {
                dfs(n - 1, k, i, result);
            }
        }

        int[] ans = new int[result.size()];
        for (int i = 0; i < result.size(); i++) {
            ans[i] = result.get(i);
        }
        return ans;
    }

    private void dfs(int remaining, int k, int num, List<Integer> result) {
        if (remaining == 0) {
            result.add(num);
            return;
        }

        int last = num % 10;

        if (last + k <= 9) {
            dfs(remaining - 1, k, num * 10 + (last + k), result);
        }

        if (k != 0 && last - k >= 0) {
            dfs(remaining - 1, k, num * 10 + (last - k), result);
        }
    }
}
